<DOC><DOCNO> AP890616-0073 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0703EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Subways     06-16 0176</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Britain-Subways,0185</SECOND><HEAD>London Commuters Battle Subway Strike</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Subway drivers today mounted their sixth 24-hourstrike in two months to back pay demands, creating travel chaos forcity commuters.   Although more subways were running than during the previousstrikes, many commuters were forced to use cars, buses, trains andtheir feet to get to work.   Spokesman Roger Shire of London Underground, which runs thesubway system, called the strike ``sheer anarchy at the public'sexpense.''   Some bus drivers in south London also staged a wildcat walkout.   The subway dispute centers on introduction of driver-only trains.   Drivers want a $99 weekly increase for operating without a guard.Management is offering $46 with extra vacation.   In another labor dispute, the National Union of Railwaymen hascalled a 24-hour strike by its 75,000 rail workers for Wednesday.   It is protesting British Rail's refusal to increase its pay offerabove 7 percent.   On the same day, the union's 10,500 members employed by LondonUnderground have been called out over management proposals to changeworking and promotion rules.</TEXT></DOC>